# Abstract

In this study, we utilized a data set of global data obtained from the USAF Climatology Center, encompassing 365 days of meteorological observations in Denver, Colorado. In our analysis we will be considering mean sea level pressure (.1 mb), mean temperature (.1 Fahrenheit), mean visibility (.1 miles), mean dew point (.1 Fahrenheit), mean wind speed (.1 knots), and maximum wind gust (.1 knots) from the data set. All the variables mentioned are being treated as continuous quantitative variables. Our analysis revealed statistically discernible evidence that temperature is predictive of sea level pressure ($t = -8.26$, $p−value < 0.0001$), visibility is predictive of sea level pressure ($t= 2.79$ , $p−value = 0.0056$), dew point is predictive of sea level pressure ($t = 4.42$, $p−value =< 0.0001$), wind speed is predictive of sea level pressure ($t =-4.33$ , $p−value = <0.0001$), and maximum wind gust is predictive of sea level pressure ($t=3.43$ , $p-value= 0.0007$). We found in our first model that about 38.35% of variability of sea level pressure is explained by the model, as described by the R-squared value, which measures the proportion of the variance in the dependent variable that is predictable from the independent variables. About 37.49% of variability of sea level pressure is explained by the first model, as explained by the adjusted R-squared value calculated. We checked the conditions for use of our first model, of which all were met, mitigating the need for transformations. We further refined our model by incorporating interaction terms, which improved the model's performance. The final interaction model, validated through cross-validation techniques, proved to be the most effective in predicting sea level pressure, with higher R-squared and adjusted R-squared values, higher ll, smaller AIC, smaller RMSE and MAE, however, the BIC was slightly higher in comparison to the original model . This study highlights the importance of considering multiple predictors and their interactions in climatology modeling, providing valuable insights for future research and practical applications.

