# Introduction

## The Data

We found our data set from data.gov in the data catalog. This data set includes global data obtained from the USAF Climatology Center. The online data files begin with 1929 and over 9000 stations’ data are available.

The daily elements included in the dataset from the different stations are: mean temperature (.1 Fahrenheit), mean dew point (.1 Fahrenheit), mean sea level pressure (.1 mb), mean station pressure (.1 mb), mean visibility (.1 miles), mean wind speed (.1 knots), maximum sustained wind speed (.1 knots), maximum wind gust (.1 knots), maximum temperature (.1 Fahrenheit), minimum temperature (.1 Fahrenheit), precipitation amount (.01 inches). snow depth (.1 inches), and indicators for occurrence of: fog, rain or drizzle, snow or ice pellets, hail, thunder, tornado/funnel cloud. The global summary of day data for 18 surface meteorological elements are derived from the synoptic/hourly observations contained in USAF DATSAV3 Surface data and Federal Climate Complex Integrated Surface Hourly (ISH).

Our specific data set includes 365 days of the above-mentioned variables in Denver, Colorado. In our analysis we will be considering mean sea level pressure (.1 mb), mean temperature (.1 Fahrenheit), mean visibility (.1 miles), mean dew point (.1 Fahrenheit), mean wind speed (.1 knots), and maximum wind gust (.1 knots) from the data set. All these variables are being treated as continuous quantitative variables. In addition to these, we added a new column to the data set indicating the season in which the observations were made, either winter, spring, summer, or fall based on the year 2018 and the region of Denver, Colorado. This new column was used when creating our scatter plot matrix as seen in @fig-4.

## Background

Weather data are checked for consistency across a region. Scientists check data sets from comparable stations to see if the data makes sense for the region and time of year. If they find inconsistencies, meteorologists methodically track down the source of the inconsistent data. At this point, original data values may be flagged as incorrect, and excluded from further processing, but they are never changed or edited, unless the error was due to incorrect transcriptions by volunteers.

Weather instruments are crucial for accurate data collection, weather forecasting and prediction, climate monitoring and research, risk management and disaster response, and environmental monitoring and resource management. This includes air quality, pollution levels, drought conditions, and water resources. Weather instruments provide precise measurements of temperature, humidity, air pressure, wind speed and direction, precipitation, and other meteorological parameters, essential for analyzing current weather conditions, detecting trends, and identifying patterns that can help predict future weather events, such as hurricanes, tornadoes, floods, and heatwaves. The data collected by these instruments are used to develop forecasts and predict weather patterns, including short-term weather events like thunderstorms and hurricanes, as well as long-term climate trends. This information helps policymakers, environmental agencies, and resource managers make informed decisions about environmental protection, conservation, and sustainable development. Also, weather instruments play a vital role in monitoring climate change and its impact on global weather patterns, ecosystems, human societies, and formulating strategies for adaptation and mitigation [@weatherstack].

The most common processing steps used to turn daily weather data into climate data products involve straightforward mathematics. Operations such as adding and averaging turn weather data into climate information. To understand climate on larger scales, climatologists’ average data from individual stations with data from other stations in the area. When combining observations, the values for each station are mathematically weighted to account for the fraction of the averaging area they represent. This keeps areas with many weather stations from being over-represented compared to areas with fewer stations.

Next is quality control, where observers verify the quality and correctness of the records immediately following their observations. For additional quality checks, observers transmit their raw data to NOAA’s National Center for Environmental Information (NCEI) on a daily or monthly basis. At NCEI, meteorologists run a basic check on all incoming data using computers to look for problems such as change points, flatliners, outliers, and excessive ranges. Once weather data has passed quality control, it becomes part of the larger data record. The data can then be processed to generate climate products, such as maps, reports, and graphs, to serve as input for computer models to help generate future climate outlooks and weather forecasts. Over time, records of weather observations help us understand the long-term conditions at each location. Climate scientists quantify long-term average conditions for each date of the year by calculating the average of observed temperature, precipitation, humidity, and others. At the beginning of every new decade, NOAA scientists calculate oﬀicial Climate Normal for the previous three decades [@climate]. These average values are the “normal” against which we compare our daily weather. Climate Normal help us answer the question: “How does today’s weather compare to average conditions over the previous three decades?”

Accurate weather forecasts are critical for public safety, emergency preparedness, agriculture, aviation, marine navigation, transportation, daily activities, scientific research, and a wide range of other applications. Pilots use weather forecasts and real-time data to plan flight routes, avoid turbulence, and make decisions about takeoff and landing. Similarly, shipping companies, railway operators, and trucking companies rely on weather information to plan routes, avoid hazardous conditions, and minimize disruptions to logistics networks. Timely and accurate weather information enables governments, emergency agencies, and communities to take proactive measures to protect lives, property, and infrastructure. Timely and accurate weather information enables authorities to issue warnings, evacuate vulnerable areas, and mobilize resources for disaster relief efforts. Renewable energy sources such as wind and solar power are highly dependent on weather conditions, with windspeed, solar radiation, and temperature affecting energy generation. Utilities use weather forecasts to anticipate demand fluctuations, optimize energy production, and manage the distribution grid effectively. Weather data recording supports a wide range of scientific research endeavors, from studying atmospheric dynamics and climate modeling to investigating the impact of weather on ecosystems and biodiversity[@weathergeeks].

## The "Why"

This data set is of interest to my partner and I because it offers a comprehensive view of historical weather patterns in Denver, Colorado, for the year 2018. This data allows us to explore various aspects of climatology and its real-world implications. By analyzing this information, we aim to understand how weather trends impact urban planning, agriculture, and public health in our region. Additionally, we are keen to investigate the effects of climate change on local weather patterns and contribute to broader environmental research. This project not only enhances our analytic skills but also provides valuable insights that can benefit our community and inform future policy decisions.

Working with data of this nature presents several challenges and limitations. The temporal and spatial resolution of the data, such as daily versus hourly measurements, might limit the depth of our analysis, and focusing on a specific location like Denver may not capture broader regional trends. External factors, such as urban development or natural events, might not be accounted for in the weather data alone, necessitating the integration of additional data sources, which can be challenging. Finally, translating our data analysis into actionable insights requires careful interpretation to avoid incorrect conclusions and recommendations. In our analysis, we are attempting to answer the following questions: Does one factor correlate with sea level pressure more than another? How does sea level pressure compare to our predictor variables?

