# Methods

To start, we created our first order linear model as a baseline for comparison to other future models. After running a ANOVA test, we then assess the assumptions of normality, summarize the model before continuing to build upon our first order linear model.,

## Full First Order Model

```{r}
model.1<-lm(SLP~TEMP+VISIB+DEWP+WDSP+GUST, data=gsod.data.clean)
summary(model.1)
```

\begin{table}[ht]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{ccccc}
  \hline\hline
 & Estimate & Std. Error & t value & Pr($>$$|$t$|$) \\ 
  \hline
(Intercept) & 1020.7689 & 2.5833 & 395.15 & <0.001 \\ 
  TEMP & -0.2758 & 0.0334 & -8.26 & <0.001 \\ 
  VISIB & 0.6891 & 0.2473 & 2.79 & 0.0056 \\ 
  DEWP & 0.1679 & 0.0380 & 4.42 & <0.001 \\ 
  WDSP & -0.5637 & 0.1302 & -4.33 & <0.001 \\ 
  GUST & 0.0028 & 0.0008 & 3.43 & 0.0007 \\ 
   \hline\hline
\end{tabular}
\caption{Summary Statistics of Model 1}
\end{table}

\newpage

The fitted model is

$\widehat Y = 1020.77 - 0.28(TEMP) + 0.69(VISIB) + 0.17(DEWP) -0.56(WDSP) - 0.0028(GUST)$.

Conclusion: There is statistically discernible evidence that temperature is predictive of sea level pressure ($t = -8.26$, $p−value < 0.0001$). There is statistically discernible evidence that visibility is predictive of (associated with) sea level pressure ($t= 2.79$ , $p−value = 0.0056$). There is statistically discernible evidence that dew point is predictive of sea level pressure ($t = 4.42$, $p−value =< 0.0001$). There is statistically discernible evidence that wind speed is predictive of sea level pressure ($t =-4.33$ , $p−value = <0.0001$). There is also statistically discernible evidence that maximum wind gust is predictive of sea level pressure ($t=3.43$ , $p-value= 0.0007$).

```{r}
summary(model.1)$r.squared
```

About 38.36% of variability of sea level pressure is explained by the model. R-squared measures the proportion of the variance in the dependent variable that is predictable from the independent variables. R-squared can be misleading because it always increases as more predictors are added to the model, even if the predictors do not improve the model significantly. One way to mitigate this issue is by calculating an adjusted R-squared value.

```{r}
summary(model.1)$adj.r.squared

```

About 37.50% of variability of sea level pressure is explained by the model. Adjusted R-Squared adjusts R-squared for the number of predictors in the model, providing a more accurate measurement of the goodness of fit, especially for models with multiple predictors. Adjusted R-squared penalizes the addition of non-significant predictors, providing a more balanced measure of model performance.

To use a multiple linear regression model effectively, several conditions should be met. First, there should be a linear relationship between the dependent variable and each of the independent variables, as seen in scatterplots or correlation coefficients. The residuals (also termed errors) of the model should be approximately normally distributed, which can be verified with a Q-Q plot. Also, the variance of the residuals should be constant across all levels of the independent variables, is essential and can be assessed with a plot of residuals versus fitted values. There should be no or little multicollinearity among the independent variables, which can be checked using a Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) values. The response variable must be continuous quantitative. Finally, the observations should be independent of each other, meaning the residuals should not be correlated and the sample should be representative. Meeting these conditions ensures that the multiple linear regression model provides reliable and valid results.

