# Conclusion

Our project analyzed data collected from the USAF Climatology Center to answer the research questions: does one factor correlated with sea level pressure more than another and how does sea level pressure compare to our predictor variables temperature, visibility, dew point, wind speed, snow depth and season? Our goal was to create a multiple linear regression model predictive of sea level pressure.

Based on the analysis and findings presented in this paper, we can conclude that our study successfully identified key predictors of sea level pressure in Denver, Colorado, using multiple linear regression models. By incorporating variables such as temperature, visibility, dew point, wind speed, and maximum wind gust, we developed a model that explains a significant portion of the variability in sea level pressure.

Our exploratory data analysis revealed that temperature had the strongest correlation with sea level pressure, while visibility had the weakest. The initial model met all necessary conditions for use, and further transformations were deemed unnecessary. The interaction model, which included interaction terms between predictors, demonstrated improved performance with higher R-Squared and Adjusted R-Squared values compared to the original model.

Stepwise model selection using AIC and BIC helped refine our model by identifying the best subset of predictors, balancing model fit and complexity. The final interaction model, validated through cross-validation techniques, proved to be the most effective in predicting sea level pressure, with lower RMSE and MAE values and higher R-Squared values.

In conclusion, our study highlights the importance of considering multiple predictors and their interactions when modeling sea level pressure. The findings provide valuable insights into the factors influencing sea level pressure and can inform future research and practical applications in climatology and environmental science.

